[13] Diarrhea, fatal - Indonesia (Irian Jaya)
Date: Wed, 26 Apr 2006
From: Andrew Jeremijenko
Source: Jakarta Post [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/Archives/ArchivesDet2.asp?FileID=20060426.D01>

Health workers are treating hundreds of villagers in Papua(Irian
Jaya)'s Jayawijaya regency to prevent the further spread of an
outbreak of a diarrheal disease that has claimed 100 lives since it
was declared an outbreak [in March 2006].
In Wamena Hospital alone, 2 more people died late Mon, 24 Apr 2006,
bringing the total number of deaths in the hospital since the
outbreak on 16 Mar 2006 to 10. Meanwhile, Jayawijaya Regency Health
Office put the number of fatalities in the villages at 90 people in a
report Tue, 25 Apr 2006. The outbreak has affected the regency's 5
districts -- Assologaima, Hubi Kosi, Kurulu, Musatfat and Wamena --
but it is feared to have spread to other regencies, such as Yahukimo
and Tolikara.
"The number of victims who died in the hospital and those reported in
remote villages, has risen to 100," said head of Jayawijaya's Health
Office, Perry Jigibalom, who earlier put the number of fatalities at 58.
In Assologaima district, where the number of people who have died of
the diarrheal disease has reached 26, 4 health workers from the
district's community health center started the mass treatment Mon, 24
Apr 2006, with 639 people treated on the first day. Treatment
continued until all of the village's 1200 residents were treated.
The 4 health workers treated each resident coming to the health post
in Muliama village office Tue, 25 Apr 2006. "Some of the residents
were suffering from diarrhea but there were those who were given
medicine as a preventive measure," said nurse Regina Tabuni. The
residents were given a tetracycline injection and provided with other
drugs, including penicillin.
The outbreak reportedly started after residents consumed contaminated
pork during a ceremony [during March 2006] in Abusa village in Kurulu
district, where hundreds of pigs had died of cholera earlier [see
below - Mod.LL]. The meat was reportedly diseased and undercooked.
Government health officials, however, have not named the
disease. Many other residents attending the ceremony were from
different districts, thus spreading the outbreak.
[Byline: Nethy Dharma Somba]
--
Dr Andrew Jeremijenko
<andrewjenk@hotmail.com>
[ProMED thanks Dr. Jeremijenko for this submission. The severity of
the illness suggests cholera and, in the next post, this is
revealed. It is important to note that hog cholera is not the same
infection as that caused by _Vibrio cholerae_ in man. The preferred
term for hog cholera is classical swine fever, but it also been
referred to as peste du porc, colera porcina, and virusschweinepest.
Classical swine fever is a highly contagious viral disease of swine
that occurs in an acute, subacute, chronic, or persistent form. In
the acute form, the disease is characterized by high fever, severe
depression, multiple superficial and internal hemorrhages, and high
morbidity and mortality. In the chronic form, the signs of
depression, anorexia, and fever are less severe than in the acute
form, and recovery is occasionally seen in mature animals.
A map of Irian Jaya (also called Papua) the Indonesian side of the
island shared by Indonesia and Papua New Guinea can be found at:
<http://www.reliefweb.int/mapc/asi_oce/reg/png.html> - Mod. LL]
