[14] Cholera - Indonesia (Irian Jaya)
Date: Fri, 28 Apr 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Jakarta Post [edited]


Test results on victims of an acute diarrheal disease in Papua's
Jayawijaya regency have confirmed that the disease, which has spread
to 2 districts in nearby Yahukimo regency, was cholera.
According to Berry Wopari of the Papua Health Office, who was
assigned to assist Jayawijaya regency in dealing with the outbreak,
cholera has killed 178 Jayawijaya residents alone since it was
declared an outbreak on 16 Mar 2006. It was previously reported as a
diarrheal disease before laboratory tests confirmed it was cholera.
In the nearby Yahukimo regency, another 33 residents had died of the disease.
Berry said the latest figure in Jayawijaya, which put the number of
fatalities at 126 on Wed, 26 Apr 2006, was based on the latest report
coming in from health posts set up across the regency. He said
laboratory tests on stool specimens conducted by the health agency's
laboratory in Surabaya early this month confirmed that the disease
was caused by the _Vibrio cholerae_ bacillus. He said the bacteria
spread through people-to-people contact and would further spread due
to poor sanitation.
The disease has reportedly spread to nearby Yahukimo regency. The
regency health office head Jacobus Mario told The Jakarta Post the
disease has killed 33 residents in Kurima and Mugi districts since 7 Apr 2006.
[Byline: Netty Dharma Somba]
--
